+const summary = `Dataset ds001_nsclc contained 50000 patients with pfs_months as the sole outcome. I treated pfs_months as a continuous endpoint because no censoring indicator was provided. Analyses used OLS mean differences, linear models, subgroup contrasts, adjusted models, and product-term interaction tests. The cohort mean PFS was ${rnd(r.yMean)} months (SD ${rnd(r.ySd)}).
+
+The strongest pattern was feature_041. Each 1-unit increase in feature_041 was associated with +${rnd(f041.beta)} months of PFS (${ptxt(f041.p)}), and the top quartile had ${rnd(f041q.diff)} months longer PFS than the bottom quartile. This association was monotonic and remained the dominant effect.
+
+Several adverse main effects were large and statistically robust. Feature_036 showed a graded decrease from 4.327 months at level 0 to 2.152 months at level 2, with an ordinal coefficient of ${rnd(f036.beta)} months per level. Feature_001=1 was ${rnd(f001.beta)} months lower than feature_001=0, feature_042=1 was ${rnd(f042.beta)} months lower than feature_042=0, and feature_015=squamous was ${rnd(f015.beta)} months lower than adenocarcinoma. Feature_025=current was also adverse: ${rnd(f025Current.beta)} months lower than non-current patients univariately and ${rnd(adj("feature_025=current").beta)} months lower than feature_025=former after adjustment. The apparent univariate advantage for feature_025=never did not persist after adjustment (${rnd(adj("feature_025=never").beta, 4)} months, ${ptxt(adj("feature_025=never").p)}).
+
+Favorable signals included feature_010=1 (+${rnd(f010.beta)} months), feature_009=1 (+${rnd(f009.beta)} months), and higher feature_056 (+${rnd(f056.beta)} months per unit; top versus bottom quartile +${rnd(f056q.diff)} months). Feature_004 was adverse both linearly (${rnd(f004.beta, 4)} months per unit) and by quartile (${rnd(f004q.diff)} months for top versus bottom quartile).
+
+Adjustment separated robust predictors from confounded univariate signals. Feature_057=1 was strongly adverse univariately (${rnd(f057.beta)} months) but was no longer significant after adjustment (${rnd(adj("feature_057").beta, 4)} months, ${ptxt(adj("feature_057").p)}). Feature_028 and feature_066 similarly lost independent signal after adjustment. Feature_051 retained a statistically significant but tiny adjusted effect (${rnd(f051a.beta, 6)} months per unit), while feature_073 was not independently significant.
+
+The most clinically meaningful heterogeneity came from interactions. The feature_010=1 and feature_009=1 combination was supra-additive: the interaction was +${rnd(ti("feature_010:feature_009").beta)} months, and the double-positive cell averaged 5.766 months compared with roughly 3.2-3.3 months in the other cells. Feature_037 weakened the favorable effects of both feature_010 and feature_009, with interactions of ${rnd(ti("feature_010:feature_037").beta)} and ${rnd(ti("feature_009:feature_037").beta)} months. Feature_057 also acted mainly as an interaction marker, attenuating feature_010 (${rnd(ti("feature_010:feature_057").beta)} months) and feature_009 (${rnd(ti("feature_057:feature_009").beta)} months) despite its nonsignificant adjusted main effect.
+
+Feature_041 interactions showed that adverse subgroups had a weaker positive feature_041 slope. The feature_041 slope was attenuated by higher feature_036 (${rnd(ti("feature_041:feature_036_raw").beta, 5)} months per feature_041 unit per feature_036 level), feature_001=1 (${rnd(ti("feature_041:feature_001_raw").beta, 5)}), feature_015=squamous (${rnd(ti("feature_041:feature_015_squamous_raw").beta, 5)}), and feature_042=1 (${rnd(ti("feature_041:feature_042_raw").beta, 5)}). Favorable markers feature_010 and feature_056 modestly strengthened the feature_041 association.
+
+Weak sparse-feature findings were less convincing. Feature_033=1 had a +${rnd(f033s.diff)} month difference but p=0.0538. Feature_029 and feature_005 had nominal unadjusted differences of ${rnd(f029s.diff)} and +${rnd(f005s.diff)} months, respectively, but these were small compared with the major effects.
+
+Overall, PFS in this cohort was dominated by feature_041, a cluster of adverse markers (feature_036, feature_001, feature_042, feature_015=squamous, feature_025=current, and feature_004), favorable markers (feature_010, feature_009, and feature_056), and strong interaction-defined subgroups. The clearest interaction subgroup was feature_010=1 plus feature_009=1, while feature_037 and feature_057 attenuated otherwise favorable patterns.`;
